[normal]For 30 years from 1910 to 1940 it warmed by 0.48C. This must be largely natural
[normal]For 30 years from 1970 to 2000 it warmed by 0.48C. 
[normal]This must be largely natural
[normal]This is said by the IPCC to be unprecedented and so must be man-made
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Produced by Mike Haseler BSc. MBA 
[normal]for the Scottish Climate &amp; Energy Forum
[normal]In Star Trek the motion picture, a mysterious and immensely powerful alien cloud called 
[normal]V'Ger
[normal] approaches Earth, destroying everything in its path. The 
[normal]Starship
[normal] enterprise (the  pinnacle of human technology) is sent out to investigate this cloud. The Enterprise penetrates the cloud only to be confronted by a vessel so advanced and so massive that it could not possibly hope to win a fight. The super advanced alien technology and power is so overwhelming that it not only swallows the Enterprise whole, but could have swallowed a whole fleet of such ships. Travelling further into the vessel, the crew finally come to the heart of the ship, where to their surprise, they do not find a super-complex “alien being”, but instead something very human, very old, very fragile, very simple and ultimately quite meaningless within its context: the V
[normal]oya
[normal]ger probe.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This is a very good analogy for the IPCC. The IPCC present an argument on climate and energy which looks as if it is mysterious and “scientific” and filling hundreds of pages must be immensely powerful and sophisticated. But at its heart is a 
[normal]a
[normal] very simple, human, fragile and ultimately meaningless argument:
[normal]It is warming – we (public sector academics) don't know why most of the change occurred, but we can't think of a better reason than all that man-made CO
[normal]2
[normal], from private business and so we think they should stop.
[normal]Just as the alien intelligence in the film was hugely technologically advanced, but in the end unable to answer a simple question about its own existence, so the IPCC is a massive machine thirsting for knowledge about the climate, but for all their endeavours they have been defeated by the simplest question: “what causes climate to change”?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]But unlike “
[normal]V'ger
[normal]” who does attempt to answer the fundamental question about its “creator”, the IPCC do not. Instead almost the entire output of the IPCC is consumed by other two questions that are largely irrelevant if they cannot answer the fundamental question about the causes of climate change. The first is akin to the proverbial “when did you last beat your wife”. Or in this case: “
[normal]how much warming are humans causing
[normal]”. Like the “when did you last beat your wife” question, the question contains an implicate assertion: that warming is caused by humans. The rest of the IPCC output is in the form “it will warm … so what WILL happen to ... hurricanes, droughts, floods, pests, plagues, rivers or blood, etc.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]But from a policy maker's point of view there are three key questions one should ask about the IPCC output:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Do they know enough about the climate to model it with enough accuracy to predict what will happen?
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]If they can predict the climate, can they determine the effects?
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Is there a good basis for government action? Is there any human activity where we are reasonably certain that the harm caused from the activity is so much greater than the benefits of that activity, that it justifies the cost of acting to end the activity? That is:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]harm-from-activity [bold] &gt; 
[normal] Benefits-[bold]of-activity  +  
[normal]cost-to-act-to-end-activity[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]To all three questions, the answer is no! Or largely no![bold]First, whilst the IPCC will assert time and time that it understands the climate, the simple fact is that all they 
[normal]know about the global climate is encapsulated in their models, of which not one predicted the current “pause” in global temperatures.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Second, as the IPCC cannot predict even the coarsest variables of the climate (temperature), it is obvious that it would be all but impossible for them to predict the finer detail of the effect of human activity, except in one respect: CO
[normal]2
[normal] is a greenhouse gas. Hidden in the detail of the IPCC report is a simple fact: that almost all experts (&amp; sceptics) are agreed that the greenhouse effect of CO
[normal]2
[normal] would cause about 1C rise in global temperature for a doubling over a century. However this good science is a small part of the theory of what is called “global warming”. As the cover image shows, the greenhouse effect of CO
[normal]2
[normal] does not explain 20
[normal]th
[normal] century warming nor does it support the vast bulk of IPCC predictions on temperature or climate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Third, using standard economic scenarios (not dreamt up figures of discount rates as used by Stern), even at the very highest predicted rates of warming, the costs of any action far outweighs the harm done: to the economy by removing cheap energy; to society through rise fuel bills and rising winter deaths, and to the environment by the industrialisation of the countryside through windmills which many rightly call “bird 
[normal]mincers
[normal]”.
[normal]The reason why the IPCC fail to understand climate is very simple. As an electronic engineer I understand that even the simplest component in the simplest circuit has noise. This is true of the climate, but  ...
[normal]… the IPCC do not understand noise or natural variation.[bold]And as a result, and unlike any real system or models used by the engineers who understand the real world is full of noise, the climate models do not include within them any concept of noise. How can this be? The real world is full of noise, but not the climate models! 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]But, natural variation or noise was stated in the first IPCC report as the null hypothesis:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We take a conservative view as a starting point namely that the magnitude of natural variability is such that all of the warming of the past century could be attributed to this cause (Note that this is not the same as denying the existence of an enhanced greenhouse effect)
[normal]1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]So the question we must ask is this: “can the effect of the rise in CO2 in the 20
[normal]th
[normal] century be distinguished from the normal level of natural variation”. The answer is clear and even the Met Office admit that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]With the 
[normal]driftless
[normal] model 
[normal][ARIMA(3,1,0)]
[normal], ... the rise in temperatures since 1880 is not significant.
[normal]2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This conclusion is supported by numerous pieces of evidence. The most obvious is shown by a comparison shown on the cover of the period from 1910-1940 with that of the period of “man-made” warming from 1970-2000. This shows the two are identical. The first is generally accepted to be largely natural, so a similar level of warming over a similar period within the same century is not only not unprecedented, but entirely normal and to be expected.
[normal]This is backed up by more technical appraisals by Green et al:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Policy-makers need to know whether prediction is possible and, if so, whether any proposed forecasting method will provide forecasts that are substantially more accurate than those from the relevant benchmark method. An inspection of global temperature data suggests that temperature is subject to irregular variations on all relevant time scales, and that variations during the late 1900s were not unusual.
[normal]3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As well as direct evidence from ice cores by Thomas et al:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The record shows that this region has warmed since the late 1950s, ... however, this warming trend is not unique. More dramatic isotopic warming (and cooling) trends occurred in the mid-nineteenth and eighteenth centuries, suggesting that at present, the effect of anthropogenic climate drivers at this location has not exceeded the natural range of climate variability in the context of the past ~300 years.
[normal]4
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Neither the IPCC nor those like the UK Met Office who contribute to it, have shown any ability to predict the main variable of this global warming namely: global temperature. This is shown by the following:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In the 1970s climate academics predicted global cooling. This did not happen. Indeed, I believe the reason CO
[normal]2  
[normal]warming was thought to be so high was because the IPCC in 1990 was in effect blaming rising CO
[normal]2
[normal] for “hiding the cooling” from their own failed prediction of global cooling.
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]No climate modeller predicted the current “pause” in global temperature.
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]All the IPCC reports have predicted surface temperature that have proven to be consistently higher than recorded and recorded  temperature is now below the range of predicted temperature given IN ALL THE IPCC REPORTS.
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The UK Met Office (considered by itself to be the foremost global warming forecasting unit) produced a series of yearly global temperature predictions. These were almost always high to such an extent, that based on the Met Office's own probabilities, I calculate that there was less than a 1 in 10,000 chance that forecasts were so poor just be chance. These “forecasts” did not produce significantly better forecasts than simply using the temperature in the last year and the yearly error was larger than the predicted warming.
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Similarly, the UK Met Office also produced a decadal global warming prediction of 0.3C temperature rise from 2004 to 2014. It has not warmed significantly in this period.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The climate modellers have not shown any skill in predicting global temperature. It is therefore reasonable to conclude, unless or until evidence is shown to the contrary, that they cannot predict global temperature.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Therefore, for all the complexity of their argument, for all the massive bulk of the “vessel” in which they deliver their message, for all the massive effort that has been undertaken to assess how a temperature rise would 
[normal]effect
[normal] the planet and undoubtedly some of it by the very best scientists in their area, at the core of the IPCC is a simple belief which is not grounded in science: that they understand the climate well enough to predict it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The sum total of all that the IPCC know is contained in these climate models. These models have proven incapable of predicting the climate, therefore for all the IPCC claim to know about the climate, the truth is that they know 
[normal]diddly
[normal] squat!
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Whilst the IPCC reports are overflowing with measurements of climate &amp; with the predictions of impacts, they are devoid of science to back the warming predictions. I think the fact the science is only limited to the greenhouse effect of CO
[normal]2,
[normal] is deliberately hidden from policy-makers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As such, given the huge uncertainty which I would argue makes it impossible to predict global temperature beyond the direct CO
[normal]2
[normal] greenhouse effect, one must ask why this is not apparent from the IPCC reports which do not distinguish between CO
[normal]2
[normal] warming and feedbacks. What one would expect to see from a careful consideration of the evidence is a hierarchy of confidence. We should expect to see a clear demarcation between those assertions which are scientific, and those which are not.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The foundation of science is careful measurement in which we rightly have high confidence. In climate research this foundation is the measurement of meteorological data such as temperature and e.g. CO
[normal]2
[normal].
[normal]As thermometer were not at every location on the earth (particularly at the poles) we can only estimate a global temperature from this network. In 2001 the first IPCC report gave a range for 20th century warming of between 0.4C and 0.8C.
[normal]CO
[normal]2
[normal] is a greenhouse gas. Using spectral data for the sun, CO
[normal]2
[normal] and other gases it is possible to work out the likely heat trapping effect of CO
[normal]2
[normal] in what is called the “Greenhouse effect”. The estimates of the greenhouse effect of CO
[normal]2
[normal] vary. A typical figure is about 1C but estimates go from 0.65C by Prof Herman Harde
[normal]5
[normal] up to the 1.2C by Hansen
[normal]6
[normal] &amp; Bony
[normal]7
[normal] used by the IPCC
[normal]8
[normal]. However, for such a key it is remarkable that only one report (AR4) states a figure for the temperature rise from CO
[normal]2
[normal] and even this is hidden under a very opaque subject heading:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.6.2.3 What Explains the Current Spread in Models’ Climate Sensitivity Estimates?[bold]“...to a doubling of atmospheric CO
[normal]2
[normal] consisted of a uniform temperature change only, with no feedbacks operating (but allowing for the enhanced 
[normal]radiative
[normal] cooling resulting from the temperature increase), the global warming from [climate models] would be around 1.2°C”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For a problem portrayed as “CO
[normal]2
[normal] warming”, for which the solution is to “cut down on CO
[normal]2
[normal] output” for which the only scientific basis of warming is this 1C of CO
[normal]2
[normal] warming
[normal]… 
[normal]is there a clearer case of hiding a key figure from policy makers?[bold]If the IPCC report is intended to support a policy of reducing [bold]CO[bold]2[bold] warming from the greenhouse effect, [bold]why isn't this the most prominent figure in the report?[bold]The greenhouse effect of CO
[normal]2
[normal] is based on well established science using the HITRAN database which is compiled from laboratory data. However as shown on the cover diagram, this effect is far too small to have caused the 20
[normal]th
[normal] century warming. So climate researchers include in their models “enhancements” which are not based on proven science except in so far as the models require them, because without these feedbacks the models would not look anything like the actual recorded global temperature.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, since the inclusion of these feedbacks is justified by the need for the models to have feedbacks in them to fit past data, then it is inherent in that justification that the models 
[normal]MUST[bold] fit future data. And if the models do not fit future data as has occurred with “the pause” this invalidates the inclusion of these feedbacks.
[normal]Fig 1: Comparison of yearly 
[normal]HadCru
[normal] &amp; UAH data with IPCC 1990 predictions
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The key justification for having these feedbacks, which are not otherwise proven in any scientific way, is that the models must fit the actual global temperature. So a key question for this inquiry is this:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Have the IPCC, or any like the Met Office advising them, shown the ability to select a measurement of global temperature and forecast it even one year in advance?
[normal]There is no doubt in my mind that the argument that “human CO
[normal]2
[normal] must be stopped” is false. This is because there are so many tenuous links to this argument that even if one link in the “chain” is wrong, even one broken link, breaks the chain.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To take a simple example. If it were found that the level of CO
[normal]2
[normal] is largely determined by surface temperature, so that the recent changes in the atmospheric level of CO
[normal]2
[normal] were not caused by man, but were instead a natural response to a natural change in global temperature (as has occurred in the past), then it would not matter if all the other steps about the warming effect of CO
[normal]2
[normal], predictions of damage, etc. were true, the whole argument is wrong because the one step is wrong. 
[normal]This also means, that even if every step in the argument is very likely to be true (for example an 85% confidence), that the overall argument is very likely to be false (14%). For the (12 step) argument below, this can be expressed mathematically as follows:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]probability (argument being right) 
[normal]              
[normal]= probability (each step being right) 
[normal]12
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]= 
[normal]0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85 x 0.85
[normal]              
[normal]Probability (argument being right) 
[normal]              
[normal]= 0.14
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The link in the argument chain for CO[bold]2[bold] causation:[bold]&#xa0;
[normal] 1.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Do we know the increase in CO[bold]2[bold] levels in the atmosphere?[bold]Reliable data is only available from 1958.
