[normal] 7.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]How much of the rise was natural?[bold]The IPCC effectively have a position that not only is the 20
[normal]th
[normal] century warming man-made, but that any natural variation has countered and hidden man-made warming. This is shown by the way that even in the first IPCC report (with the lowest predicted warming) their predicted warming was significantly higher than the current trend. This scale of prediction can be explained if they expected about 0.07C/decade additional cooling which they perceived as being added to observed warming.
[normal]However, the reality is that in the last 15 or so years the climate has not warmed contrary to all the IPCC model predictions. This shows that even if there were man-made warming as large as they suggest, then 
[normal]there is also natural variation of the same scale[bold] whose cooling influence exactly matches their predicted warming
[normal].[bold]Perhaps more importantly even the Met Office have admitted that there is a statistical test that shows the 20
[normal]th
[normal] century warming cannot be distinguished from noise. 
[normal]2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 8.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Are there feedbacks? If so, how large?[bold]Asserting that the 20
[normal]th
[normal] century warming is due to humans (as well as “hidden” warming of as much as 0.07C/decade) the IPCC are in affect claiming there must be “feedbacks” without needing to prove them. The true nature of these unproven and therefore unscientific feedbacks are hidden from policy makers. But as fig 2 shows their effect is massive and dominates the warming predictions. They mean that a greenhouse effect of doubling CO
[normal]2
[normal] over the next century which can be calculated as about 1C is multiplied up by these unproven feedback effects by 1.5x to 5.5x. So, for each 1C of warming from the greenhouse effect, there is up to an additional 4.5C  being caused by these unproven “feedbacks”. 
[normal]This is a ridiculous figure which if true would mean that the 0.35C of greenhouse warming over the 20
[normal]th
[normal] century had caused 1.9C warming of which 1.55C must be natural cooling – 
[normal]making natural variation much [bold]much[bold] larger than man-made effects. [bold]  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 9.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Can they predict the rise in temperature from CO[bold]2[bold]?[bold]I do not think the temperature predictions is determined by CO
[normal]2
[normal] warming. As such it is doubtful that if a different figure of CO
[normal]2
[normal] warming is used, that the predicted warming figures would be different. This is because these are largely based on the inference:
[normal]              
[normal] GREENHOUSE-EFFECT  x FEEDBACK = OBSERVED-WARMING-TREND
[normal]So if the CO
[normal]2
[normal] effect is 30% smaller (as suggested by Harde
[normal]5
[normal]) then the feedbacks would be changed to be 30% larger so that the models matched the observed warming. This means the predicted warming is largely given by the following:
[normal]              
[normal] PREDICTED-WARMING-TREND = GREENHOUSE-EFFECT x FEEDBACK
[normal]or
[normal]              
[normal] PREDICTED-WARMING-TREND = OBSERVED-WARMING-TREND
[normal]So predicted trend is largely independent of the actual greenhouse effect of CO
[normal]2
[normal]. This may explain why the CO
[normal]2
[normal] greenhouse effect is so unimportant to the IPCC, that the actual temperature change from CO
[normal]2  
[normal]greenhouse warming has only been stated once in any IPCC report and then it was effectively hidden from policy makers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 10.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What are the predicted effects of this rise in terms of severe weather rising sea level etc.[bold](a)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]When does warming stop being beneficial?
[normal]There are known benefits such as the beneficial effect of CO
[normal]2
[normal] on plant growth and warmer temperatures on winter deaths. Global temperatures have always varied and typically historians have linked colder periods to historical problems. So, initially we expect warming to be beneficial, but at what temperature will this end?
[normal](b)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What is the cost of these predicted effects?
[normal]Largely unknown but estimates always seem to the worst possible scenario and the positive benefits such as CO
[normal]2
[normal] being a plant food and winter deaths are ignored?
[normal](c)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]What is the cost of reducing CO
[normal]2
[normal]?
[normal]Even at the highest levels of warming, Lord Monckton
[normal]10
[normal] has calculated that it vastly more expensive to act on CO
[normal]2
[normal] than to wait to see whether problems arise.
[normal](d)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Even if costs of acting are less than costs of impacts, can we actually do anything?
[normal]All economic activity consumes energy. Therefore anything we attempt to do such as manufacturing wind or Solar PV consumes vast amounts of energy which in turn release CO
[normal]2.
[normal] Some estimate this is greater than the CO
[normal]2
[normal] reduction.
[normal](e)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Even if we can do anything is the current policy favouring wind the answer?
[normal]Even if we needed to reduce CO
[normal]2
[normal], it is doubtful the current policies are “the answer” as much of the policy around 2000 was driven by the wind developers for the wind developers.
[normal](f)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]If we can increase temperature, can't we geo-engineering a way to reduce it?. 
[normal]Could we e.g. just carry on as we are … and in a very simplistic way “explode a few nuclear bombs” causing the so called nuclear winter.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 11.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Even if the benefits exceed the cost, what is the opportunity cost?[bold] 
[normal]Could we spend the money of better things like e.g. a cure for cancer. In other words, would future generations prefer we had invested in a cure for cancer or trying to reduce warming?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 12.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]And lastly even if it’s financially a good idea, is it morally right?[bold] 
[normal]Is it right that the poorest in society are for example denied fuel in Scotland where there are estimates that 50% are in fuel poverty. Is it right that we ask the poor of today to sacrifice in order to make the richer part of the richer society of the future even richer?
[normal]And what if the real solution were found to be to cut the world population? A logical solution would be for us all to continue using the same amount of fossil fuel but cut the number of people. But would it be morally right to e.g. sterilise a significant proportion of women to prevent population growth? 
[normal]Are there some things where morality means we have to put up with minor problems like some small amounts of warming even if there is an overall benefit to society from acting?
